{%- comment -%}
  Product Form — quantity + add to cart + dynamic checkout button.
  Birebir from source PDP: quantity selector + ATC + share.
  Uses Shopify {% form 'product' %} with variant ID.

  Accepts:
  - product:              {Object}  Shopify product
  - show_dynamic_checkout {Boolean} render the Shop Pay / Buy it now button.
                                    Defaults to true (Theme Store best practice).
  - show_quantity         {Boolean} render the quantity stepper.
                                    Defaults to true. Pass false to hide the
                                    stepper for layouts where qty=1 is implied
                                    (showroom buy block, etc).
                                    R166: snippet still posts qty=1 via a
                                    hidden input when stepper is hidden so
                                    the form submit shape stays consistent.
  - atc_label             {String}  Override the Add-to-cart button label.
                                    Defaults to `kt.product.add_to_cart` t-key.
                                    Lets the showroom's "Reserve this item"
                                    / "Order sample" copy reach the same
                                    canonical product form.
  - section:              {Object}  The caller section. Used to suffix DOM
                                    IDs (e.g. `Quantity-<id>-<section.id>`)
                                    so the same product rendered through
                                    BOTH main-product and a featured-product
                                    block doesn't collide on duplicate IDs.
                                    R296 — Theme Store WCAG 4.1.1 fix.
{%- endcomment -%}

{%- assign current_variant = product.selected_or_first_available_variant -%}
{%- comment -%}
  R296 — Build a unique form-ID suffix. When the caller passes `section`
  we use `section.id`; otherwise we fall back to `product.id` so callers
  outside a section context (rare — only the cart upsell snippet) still
  get a unique form. Suffixed IDs prevent duplicate-ID WCAG 4.1.1 fails
  when the same snippet renders twice on one page (e.g. PDP + a
  featured-product block referencing the same product).
{%- endcomment -%}
{%- assign pf_uid = product.id -%}
{%- if section and section.id -%}
  {%- assign pf_uid = product.id | append: '-' | append: section.id -%}
{%- endif -%}
{%- comment -%}
  R298 — Dynamic Checkout (Shop Pay / Buy it now / Apple Pay / Google Pay)
  is now ALWAYS rendered. Shopify's Online Store sales channel +
  Theme Store submission requirements mandate `{{ form | payment_button }}`
  inside every `{% form 'product' %}`. A prior session disabled it because
  the Shop Pay button's closed-shadow-DOM blue palette didn't match the
  storefront's dark CTA language — but Theme Store reviewers reject themes
  that omit the accelerated checkout button regardless of palette concerns
  (merchants disable individual buttons in Settings → Payments if needed).
  The kwarg name `show_dynamic_checkout` is preserved so legacy callers
  that pass `false` are honoured for backwards-compat, but it now defaults
  to `true` for any new caller.
{%- endcomment -%}
{%- if show_dynamic_checkout == nil -%}
  {%- assign show_dynamic_checkout = true -%}
{%- endif -%}
{%- if show_quantity == nil -%}
  {%- assign show_quantity = true -%}
{%- endif -%}

{%- comment -%}
  Wrapping div carries the `data-product-form` selector hook and the
  product id so product-form.js can find the form without relying on
  hyphenated kwargs inside the `{% form %}` tag — Liquid's kwarg parser
  accepts `data-*: value` via a Shopify-specific extension, but passing
  empty strings (`data-product-form: ''`) is brittle and some linters
  flag the hyphens as arithmetic tokens. A plain <div> wrapper keeps
  the selector hooks out of Liquid-tag territory entirely.
{%- endcomment -%}
<div class="kt-product-form" data-product-form data-product-id="{{ product.id }}" data-product-url="{{ product.url }}">
{%- form 'product', product, id: 'ProductForm-' | append: pf_uid -%}
  <input type="hidden" name="id" value="{{ current_variant.id }}" data-variant-id>

  {%- comment -%}
    Gift card recipient form — only rendered when the product being
    purchased is itself a gift card (Shopify's product.gift_card?
    object). When set, the customer can opt in to emailing the
    issued card directly to a recipient on a scheduled date.
    Required for any store that sells digital gift cards — Theme
    Store flags the absence as a missing mandatory feature.
  {%- endcomment -%}
  {%- if product.gift_card? -%}
    {%- render 'gift-card-recipient-form', product: product, form: form, section: section -%}
    <script src="{{ 'gift-card-recipient.js' | asset_url }}" defer="defer"></script>
  {%- endif -%}

  {%- comment -%}
    Selling-plan picker — Shopify Theme Store rule SUB-01 + SUB-03:
    the `<input name="selling_plan">` MUST live inside the
    `{% form 'product' %}` block. R86 moved this here from
    main-product.liquid (which previously rendered it as a sibling
    BEFORE invoking product-form, leaving the input outside the
    form scope and breaking native non-JS submission + the JS
    variant-change → plan-update path). featured-product.liquid
    has its own form/picker pair already, so this render is gated
    on the product actually having selling plans (silent no-op
    otherwise).
  {%- endcomment -%}
  {%- if product.selling_plan_groups.size > 0 -%}
    {%- render 'product-selling-plans', product: product, current_variant: current_variant, section: section -%}
  {%- endif -%}

  {%- comment -%}
    Quantity-rule resolution. Merchants can now declare a
    variant-level quantity rule via admin → Product → Variants →
    Quantity rules (min / max / increment, e.g. "sold in packs of 6").
    Shopify exposes these via `variant.quantity_rule.{min,max,increment}`
    — all three default to sensible integers (1/nil/1) when the
    merchant hasn't configured them, so this logic is safe for every
    product.

    Without respecting the rule:
      - A case-of-6 item renders `min=1 step=1 value=1` and every
        add-to-cart fails with "Quantity must be a multiple of 6."
      - A max-500 bulk variant can be over-ordered; Shopify rejects
        silently at checkout.
  {%- endcomment -%}
  {%- assign qty_min = current_variant.quantity_rule.min | default: 1 -%}
  {%- assign qty_step = current_variant.quantity_rule.increment | default: 1 -%}
  {%- assign qty_max = current_variant.quantity_rule.max -%}

  {%- comment -%} Quantity + Add to Cart row {%- endcomment -%}
  <div class="kt-product-form__row{% unless show_quantity %} kt-product-form__row--no-qty{% endunless %}">
    {%- comment -%}
      Quantity selector — gated on `show_quantity`. When the host
      layout opts out of the visible stepper (showroom buy block,
      "1-click reserve" surface, etc.) we still post a hidden
      `quantity` input so /cart/add receives the canonical form
      shape. Without that hidden input the form submit would post
      no quantity, and Shopify's cart endpoint defaults to qty=1
      silently — which works today but breaks the moment the
      product has a quantity_rule.min > 1 (case-of-6 items),
      because the default qty=1 gets rejected at the cart layer.
    {%- endcomment -%}
    {%- if show_quantity -%}
      {%- comment -%}
        R296 — `product.title` is merchant-controlled but Theme Store
        rejects any interpolation into HTML attributes without `| escape`
        (product names can legally contain `"` and `<`). Pre-escape once;
        the resulting string is safe for use in both aria-labels below.
      {%- endcomment -%}
      {%- assign safe_product_title = product.title | escape -%}
      <div class="kt-product-form__qty">
        <button type="button" class="kt-product-form__qty-btn" data-qty-minus aria-label="{{ 'kt.product.quantity.decrease' | t: title: safe_product_title }}">
          <svg aria-hidden="true" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><line x1="5" y1="12" x2="19" y2="12"></line></svg>
        </button>
        <input
          type="number"
          name="quantity"
          id="Quantity-{{ pf_uid }}"
          value="{{ qty_min }}"
          min="{{ qty_min }}"
          step="{{ qty_step }}"
          {% if qty_max != blank %}max="{{ qty_max }}"{% endif %}
          inputmode="numeric"
          pattern="[0-9]*"
          class="kt-product-form__qty-input"
          data-qty-input
          data-qty-min="{{ qty_min }}"
          data-qty-step="{{ qty_step }}"
          {% if qty_max != blank %}data-qty-max="{{ qty_max }}"{% endif %}
          aria-label="{{ 'kt.product.quantity.label' | t }}"
        >
        <button type="button" class="kt-product-form__qty-btn" data-qty-plus aria-label="{{ 'kt.product.quantity.increase' | t: title: safe_product_title }}">
          {% render 'icon-plus' %}
        </button>
      </div>

      {%- comment -%}
        Case-pack / quantity-rule indicator — required by Shopify B2B
        documentation when a variant ships with `quantity_rule.increment > 1`
        or `min > 1` or a finite `max`. Without a visible message, customers
        get cryptic 422s from /cart/add and Theme Store reviewers flag
        opaque B2B UX as a rejection. Each branch resolves to a localised
        sentence so the customer understands the contract before submit.
      {%- endcomment -%}
      {%- if qty_step > 1 or qty_min > 1 or qty_max != blank -%}
        <p class="kt-product-form__qty-rule" data-qty-rule role="note">
          {%- if qty_step > 1 -%}
            {{ 'kt.product.quantity.rule_increment_html' | t: count: qty_step }}
          {%- elsif qty_min > 1 -%}
            {{ 'kt.product.quantity.rule_min_html' | t: count: qty_min }}
          {%- elsif qty_max != blank -%}
            {{ 'kt.product.quantity.rule_max_html' | t: count: qty_max }}
          {%- endif -%}
        </p>
      {%- endif -%}
    {%- else -%}
      <input type="hidden" name="quantity" value="{{ qty_min }}">
    {%- endif -%}

    {%- comment -%}
      Add to Cart button — two icons rendered, CSS swaps based on :disabled.

      Also disabled when the product REQUIRES a selling plan
      (subscription-only item with no one-time-purchase path). Without
      this gate, the ATC posts to /cart/add without a `selling_plan`
      param and Shopify rejects with a generic error. Gate here so the
      customer sees a clear disabled state + localised "Subscription
      required" copy instead.
    {%- endcomment -%}
    {%- comment -%}
      ATC disabled on sold-out only. requires_selling_plan no longer
      disables the button because snippets/product-selling-plans.liquid
      (rendered above) auto-selects a plan for subscription-only
      products, so the hidden `selling_plan` field is populated before
      the submit.
    {%- endcomment -%}
    {%- assign atc_disabled = false -%}
    {%- unless current_variant.available -%}{%- assign atc_disabled = true -%}{%- endunless -%}
    <button
      type="submit"
      class="kt-product-form__atc"
      {% if atc_disabled %}disabled{% endif %}
      data-add-to-cart
    >
      {%- comment -%}
        R269 — The previous markup carried TWO inline SVGs (shopping
        bag for available + X-in-circle for sold-out) that toggled
        visibility via CSS based on the `:disabled` selector. The
        sold-out icon read as visually heavy/jarring next to the
        button text — the merchant reported "X icon ne alaka,
        button gri kalıyor disabled gibi" on a test product with
        sold-out variant. The gray disabled background + "Sold out"
        text already convey the unavailable semantic; the X icon
        added visual noise without information. Removed entirely.
        The button keeps its text-only treatment in both states.
      {%- endcomment -%}
      <span data-add-to-cart-text>
        {%- if current_variant.available -%}
          {%- comment -%}
            R166: `atc_label` lets the showroom buy block surface
            "Reserve this item" / "Order sample" copy through the
            same canonical form. Falls back to the localized
            default. Escaped because the value can come from
            merchant input.
          {%- endcomment -%}
          {%- if atc_label != blank -%}
            {{ atc_label | escape }}
          {%- else -%}
            {{ 'kt.product.add_to_cart' | t }}
          {%- endif -%}
        {%- else -%}
          {{ 'kt.product.sold_out' | t }}
        {%- endif -%}
      </span>
    </button>
  </div>

  {%- comment -%}
    Pre-order badge — shown when the variant is out of stock BUT the
    merchant has `inventory_policy: 'continue'` (keep selling when
    out of stock). Without this badge the customer can't distinguish
    "available now" from "ordered, ships when restocked" — both show
    the default Add-to-Cart button. Gated on both Shopify-tracked
    inventory and out-of-stock state to avoid false-positive badging
    on products whose merchant doesn't track stock at all.
  {%- endcomment -%}
  {%- comment -%}
    R298 — Pre-order badge is now ALWAYS rendered in the DOM with the
    `hidden` attribute toggled to match the initial variant state. The
    `[data-preorder]` hook lets `assets/product-form.js`'s `updateVariant`
    atomically show/hide the badge when the customer switches between
    in-stock and backorderable-out-of-stock variants. Previously the
    badge was only emitted when the initial variant happened to be a
    pre-order — variant change couldn't toggle it on/off because the
    element didn't exist in the DOM. Same atomic-update bug class the
    low-stock badge was already fixed for.
  {%- endcomment -%}
  {%- assign preorder_initial_hidden = true -%}
  {%- if current_variant.inventory_management == 'shopify' and current_variant.inventory_quantity <= 0 and current_variant.inventory_policy == 'continue' -%}
    {%- assign preorder_initial_hidden = false -%}
  {%- endif -%}
  <p class="kt-product-form__preorder" data-preorder role="note"{% if preorder_initial_hidden %} hidden{% endif %}>
    {{ 'kt.product.preorder' | t }}
  </p>

  {%- comment -%}
    Error sentinel — populated by product-form.js when /cart/add.js
    responds with an error (out of stock, quantity limit, network).
    Hidden by default; JS toggles [hidden] and fills textContent.
  {%- endcomment -%}
  <div class="kt-product-form__error" data-product-form-error role="alert" hidden></div>

  {%- comment -%} Dynamic Checkout Button (Buy Now / Shop Pay etc.) {%- endcomment -%}
  {%- if show_dynamic_checkout -%}
    <div class="kt-product-form__dynamic-checkout">
      {{ form | payment_button }}
    </div>
  {%- endif -%}

  {%- comment -%}
    Shop Pay Installments banner — Theme Store paid mandatory feature
    (Section 4). `{{ form | payment_terms }}` renders Shopify's native
    `<shopify-payment-terms>` custom element which only displays when
    the merchant has Shop Pay Installments enabled AND the product
    price meets the threshold; otherwise it emits nothing. Safe to
    always include.
  {%- endcomment -%}
  <div class="kt-product-form__installments">
    {{ form | payment_terms }}
  </div>

  {%- comment -%}
    Share — Web Share API with clipboard fallback. Privacy-safe: no
    tracking, no external services. The Shopify Theme Store treats
    save-for-later / favourites features as app territory (merchants
    install their preferred wishlist app, which ships an app block
    drop zone), so this theme deliberately exposes only the share
    affordance here.
  {%- endcomment -%}
  <div class="kt-product-form__actions">
    <button
      type="button"
      class="kt-product-form__action-btn"
      data-share-btn
      data-share-title="{{ product.title | escape }}"
      data-share-url="{{ shop.url }}{{ product.url }}"
      data-label-default="{{ 'kt.product.share' | t }}"
      data-label-copied="{{ 'kt.product.share_copied' | t }}"
    >
      <svg aria-hidden="true" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round">
        <circle cx="18" cy="5" r="3"></circle>
        <circle cx="6" cy="12" r="3"></circle>
        <circle cx="18" cy="19" r="3"></circle>
        <line x1="8.59" y1="13.51" x2="15.42" y2="17.49"></line>
        <line x1="15.41" y1="6.51" x2="8.59" y2="10.49"></line>
      </svg>
      <span data-share-label>{{ 'kt.product.share' | t }}</span>
    </button>
  </div>
{%- endform -%}
</div>
